-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Deuteronomy — Part 2 (Chapters 11–20)
-- 3 difficulties × 10 chapters = 160 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 30
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 50
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 80
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 11 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'kids', 1, 'What did God promise to send in its season if Israel obeyed Him?', 'Rain for the land', 'Manna from heaven', 'Fire on the altar', 'Wind from the sea', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:14 — "That I will give you the rain of your land in his due season, the first rain and the latter rain, that thou mayest gather in thy corn, and thy wine, and thine oil."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'kids', 2, 'What two mountains did Moses say would have a blessing on one and a curse on the other?', 'Gerizim and Ebal', 'Sinai and Horeb', 'Zion and Carmel', 'Nebo and Pisgah', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:29 — "thou shalt put the blessing upon mount Gerizim, and the curse upon mount Ebal."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'kids', 3, 'What did God say would happen to Israel''s enemies if they obeyed His commandments?', 'God would drive out the nations before them', 'The nations would become their servants', 'The nations would flee to the desert', 'The nations would bring them gifts', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:23 — "Then will the LORD drive out all these nations from before you, and ye shall possess greater nations and mightier than yourselves."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'teens', 1, 'What did Moses say Israel''s eyes had seen regarding God''s great acts in Egypt?', 'The chastisement of Pharaoh and of all his land and what He did to the army of Egypt', 'The building of the tabernacle and the giving of the law', 'The fire and cloud that led them through the wilderness', 'The victory at Jericho before they entered', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:3-4 — "And his miracles, and his acts, which he did in the midst of Egypt...And what he did unto the army of Egypt, unto their horses, and to their chariots."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'teens', 2, 'How does Moses contrast the land of Canaan with the land of Egypt regarding water?', 'Egypt was watered by foot like a garden; Canaan drank rain from heaven', 'Canaan had rivers like Egypt; Egypt depended on rain', 'Both lands needed irrigation from rivers', 'Egypt had rain but Canaan had none', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:10-11 — "For the land, whither thou goest in to possess it, is not as the land of Egypt...But the land...drinketh water of the rain of heaven."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'teens', 3, 'What were the Israelites commanded to do with God''s words — where were they to bind and write them?', 'Bind them as a sign on their hand, between their eyes, and write them on doorposts and gates', 'Only recite them in the tabernacle on holy days', 'Engrave them on stones at the city entrance', 'Write them on scrolls and keep them in the ark', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:18 — "Therefore shall ye lay up these my words in your heart and in your soul, and bind them for a sign upon your hand, that they may be as frontlets between your eyes."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'teens', 4, 'What promise did God make about the extent of Israel''s land if they kept His commandments?', 'From the wilderness and Lebanon, from the Euphrates to the uttermost sea', 'From the Nile to the Euphrates, all of the Fertile Crescent', 'From the Jordan to the Mediterranean and from Sinai to Syria', 'From Beersheba to Dan, the full length of Canaan', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:24 — "Every place whereon the soles of your feet shall tread shall be yours: from the wilderness and Lebanon, from the river, the river Euphrates, even unto the uttermost sea shall your coast be."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'teens', 5, 'What choice did Moses set before Israel at the end of chapter 11, and where were they to be proclaimed?', 'A blessing and a curse — blessing for obedience and curse for disobedience, proclaimed at Gerizim and Ebal', 'Life and death — life for the righteous and death for sinners, at the Jordan crossing', 'Peace and war — peace if they obeyed, war if they rebelled, at Shechem', 'Abundance and famine — abundance for obedience, famine for idolatry, at Shiloh', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:26-29 — "Behold, I set before you this day a blessing and a curse...And it shall come to pass, when the LORD thy God hath brought thee in...that thou shalt put the blessing upon mount Gerizim, and the curse upon mount Ebal."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 1, 'What historical events does Moses cite in Deuteronomy 11:6 as evidence of God''s disciplinary power within Israel itself?', 'What God did to Dathan and Abiram — the earth swallowed them and their households', 'The deaths of those who made the golden calf', 'The plague that followed the rebellion of Korah', 'The deaths of the firstborn of those who murmured at Kadesh', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:6 — "And what he did unto Dathan and Abiram...whom the earth opened her mouth, and swallowed them up, and their households, and their tents, and all the substance that was in their possession."'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 2, 'How does the agricultural contrast between Egypt and Canaan in Deuteronomy 11:10-12 function theologically?', 'It shows Canaan is superior geographically and therefore the natural reward for obedience', 'Canaan''s dependence on rain makes it a land under God''s direct care, where blessing or drought reflects covenant faithfulness', 'It proves Israel would need less work in Canaan than in Egypt', 'It demonstrates that farming methods in Canaan were more advanced', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:11-12 — "the land of Canaan...drinketh water of the rain of heaven: A land which the LORD thy God careth for: the eyes of the LORD thy God are always upon it, from the beginning of the year even unto the end of the year." Canaan''s rain dependency ties obedience directly to God''s ongoing providential care.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 3, 'What are the "first rain and the latter rain" promised in Deuteronomy 11:14, and what is their agricultural and prophetic significance?', 'The early (autumn) rain for planting and the late (spring) rain for harvest — used in James 5:7 to picture Christ''s return', 'Two annual floods of the Jordan providing irrigation for all of Canaan', 'Morning and evening dew that sustained crops year-round', 'Rain at Passover and rain at Tabernacles marking the sacred calendar', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:14 — "the first rain and the latter rain." James 5:7 uses this exact phrase: "Behold, the husbandman waiteth for the precious fruit of the earth, and hath long patience for it, until he receive the early and latter rain." The pattern is fulfilled in Christ''s first and second comings.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 4, 'What does Deuteronomy 11:13 mean by "serve him with all your heart and with all your soul," and how does Jesus cite this passage?', 'It means wholehearted love, not merely external compliance — cited by Jesus as the greatest commandment', 'It refers to the Levitical service in the tabernacle', 'It means Israel must keep all 613 commandments perfectly', 'It was only a command for priests and Levites', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:13 anticipates Deuteronomy 6:5. Jesus quotes the Shema saying "Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul" (Matthew 22:37), identifying this wholehearted devotion as the first and greatest commandment.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 5, 'What does Moses mean when he says in Deuteronomy 11:2 that he speaks to those who "have not seen the chastisement of the LORD"?', 'The new generation had not witnessed the Exodus judgments firsthand, yet must appropriate them by faith through teaching', 'Moses was saying the younger generation was exempt from God''s discipline', 'He was excluding the Levites who had been children during the Exodus', 'He acknowledged that the older generation had died and therefore the covenant was void', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:2 — "And know ye this day: for I speak not with your children which have not known, and which have not seen the chastisement of the LORD your God." Moses distinguishes the generation he addresses from those who witnessed events personally, grounding obedience in transmitted knowledge.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 6, 'How do Gerizim and Ebal anticipate the covenant renewal ceremony described in detail in Deuteronomy 27-28?', 'They are simply geographic landmarks with no deeper significance', 'They serve as the divinely appointed staging ground for the public proclamation of blessing and curse upon entry into the land, fulfilled in Joshua 8:30-35', 'They were the sites of the two altars built by Abraham', 'Moses chose them arbitrarily for their elevation', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:29 plants the seed that blossoms in Deuteronomy 27-28 and is executed in Joshua 8:33-35 — "all Israel, and their elders...stood on this side the ark...in the presence of the priests...half of them over against mount Gerizim, and half of them over against mount Ebal." The ceremony enacted the covenant terms nationally.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 7, 'What is the literary and theological significance of the phrase "the land whither ye go to possess it" recurring throughout Deuteronomy 11?', 'It is a legal formula indicating Israel''s title deed to Canaan', 'It functions as a covenant refrain anchoring future obedience to the promised inheritance, holding gift and responsibility in tension', 'It was Moses'' way of reminding Israel that the conquest would be easy', 'It indicates the land was already fully cleared of its inhabitants', 'a', 'The phrase recurs in verses 8, 10, 11, 29, and 31 creating a rhetorical frame: gift (entering the land) and demand (keeping commandments) are inseparable. The inheritance is both assured and conditional, a pattern running through the entire covenant structure of Deuteronomy.'),
('Deuteronomy', 11, 'adults', 8, 'How does the command to teach God''s words diligently to children (Deuteronomy 11:19) relate to the concept of covenant succession?', 'It was only relevant until Israel entered Canaan', 'It establishes intergenerational transmission of covenant knowledge as the primary means by which each generation appropriates the blessings of the covenant', 'It shows that only Levites were responsible for religious education', 'It was superseded by the written Torah once the canon was complete', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 11:19 — "And ye shall teach them your children, speaking of them when thou sittest in thine house, and when thou walkest by the way, when thou liest down, and when thou risest up." This mirrors Deuteronomy 6:7 and grounds the covenant''s continuity in faithful domestic instruction, not merely institutional religion.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 12 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'kids', 1, 'What did God say Israel must do to the altars and idols of the nations in Canaan?', 'Destroy them completely', 'Leave them for the Levites', 'Move them to Jerusalem', 'Cover them with earth', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:2-3 — "Ye shall utterly destroy all the places, wherein the nations which ye shall possess served their gods...And ye shall overthrow their altars, and break their pillars."'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'kids', 2, 'Where did God say Israel must bring their offerings and sacrifices?', 'The place God would choose to put His name', 'Wherever they lived in the land', 'Any hilltop in Israel', 'The tent of meeting in the desert', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:5 — "But unto the place which the LORD your God shall choose out of all your tribes to put his name there, even unto his habitation shall ye seek, and thither thou shalt come."'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'kids', 3, 'What were Israelites forbidden to eat when they killed animals for food?', 'The blood', 'The fat of the animal', 'The liver', 'The firstborn animals', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:16 — "Only ye shall not eat the blood; ye shall pour it upon the earth as water."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'teens', 1, 'What was the main reason God commanded a single central place of worship rather than many local shrines?', 'To prevent Israel from imitating Canaanite worship at multiple high places', 'To make the priests wealthier through concentrated tithes', 'To ensure the tribes remained physically close to each other', 'To reduce the number of animals needed for sacrifice', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:4 — "Ye shall not do so unto the LORD your God." The central sanctuary prevented syncretism with Canaanite religion which used numerous local high places, each potentially corrupting Israel''s pure worship.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'teens', 2, 'What types of offerings and gifts does Deuteronomy 12:6 list that were to be brought to the central sanctuary?', 'Burnt offerings, sacrifices, tithes, heave offerings, vows, freewill offerings, and firstlings', 'Only the annual Passover lamb', 'Just the firstfruits and tithes', 'The sin offering and guilt offering exclusively', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:6 — "And thither ye shall bring your burnt offerings, and your sacrifices, and your tithes, and heave offerings of your hand, and your vows, and your freewill offerings, and the firstlings of your herds and of your flocks."'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'teens', 3, 'What concession did God make in Deuteronomy 12 for eating meat when Israel was far from the central sanctuary?', 'They could slaughter and eat meat at home without bringing it to the altar, as long as they poured out the blood', 'They could not eat meat at all unless at the sanctuary', 'They had to bring every animal to the nearest Levitical city', 'They could only eat fish and fowl far from the sanctuary', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:15 — "Notwithstanding thou mayest kill and eat flesh in all thy gates...after the blessing of the LORD thy God which he hath given thee." And verse 16: "Only ye shall not eat the blood."'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'teens', 4, 'What warning did Moses give about inquiring after the religious practices of the nations Israel would displace?', 'Take heed to thyself that thou be not snared by following them', 'Study their practices to understand their errors', 'The nations'' practices were harmless if not formally adopted', 'Younger Israelites could observe them out of curiosity', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:30 — "Take heed to thyself that thou be not snared by following them...and that thou enquire not after their gods, saying, How did these nations serve their gods?"'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'teens', 5, 'What horrible practice of the Canaanites does Moses specifically mention at the end of Deuteronomy 12 as something Israel must never do?', 'Burning their sons and daughters in the fire to their gods', 'Eating animals sacrificed to idols', 'Building temples on high mountains', 'Using carved images in worship', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:31 — "for every abomination to the LORD, which he hateth, have they done unto their gods; for even their sons and their daughters they have burnt in the fire to their gods."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological principle behind the command in Deuteronomy 12:4 — "Ye shall not do so unto the LORD your God"?', 'God''s worship must be governed by His own revealed will, not human invention or cultural borrowing', 'Israel was simply required to use different locations than the Canaanites', 'The prohibition was temporary until the temple was built', 'It was only addressing the specific altars of Baal and Asherah', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:4 prohibits worshipping the true God in the manner pagans worshipped false gods. This establishes the regulative principle of worship — that God alone determines acceptable worship — a foundational concept in both Old and New Testament theology (John 4:23-24).'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 2, 'How does Deuteronomy 12:5 — "the place which the LORD your God shall choose" — relate to the later establishment of Jerusalem and the temple?', 'Jerusalem was chosen by David, not by God, so the verse was never fully fulfilled', 'It anticipates Jerusalem and the temple as the definitive fulfillment — 2 Chronicles 6:6 confirms God chose Jerusalem', 'Any city in Israel was equally acceptable as a central sanctuary', 'The verse was fulfilled by the tabernacle at Shiloh permanently', 'a', '2 Chronicles 6:6 records God saying, "But I have chosen Jerusalem, that my name might be there." The Deuteronomic formula "the place which the LORD shall choose" points forward to Jerusalem, fulfilled when Solomon''s temple was dedicated as God''s earthly dwelling.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 3, 'What is the significance of distinguishing between "holy things" that must be eaten at the sanctuary (Deuteronomy 12:17-18) and ordinary meat that could be eaten at home (verse 15)?', 'It creates a two-tier system separating sacred and secular use of food within covenant life', 'It shows that tithes and vow offerings were spiritually superior to regular food', 'It was a dietary health law unrelated to worship', 'It only applied to Levites and priests', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:17-18 lists tithes of grain, wine, oil, firstlings, vows, and freewill offerings as requiring sanctuary consumption. Verse 15 permits domestic slaughter for regular meals. This distinction structures Israelite life around a sacred center while accommodating normal daily life throughout the land.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 4, 'What is the stated reason for the absolute prohibition on consuming blood in Deuteronomy 12:23?', 'The blood is the life, and therefore it belongs to God alone', 'Blood was unclean and caused disease', 'Only the priests could consume blood in sacred rituals', 'Blood was reserved for the red heifer purification rite', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:23 — "Only be sure that thou eat not the blood: for the blood is the life; and thou mayest not eat the life with the flesh." The blood''s identification with life makes it uniquely God''s property, consistent with the atonement theology of Leviticus 17:11.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 5, 'How does Deuteronomy 12:8 — "Ye shall not do after all the things that we do here this day, every man whatsoever is right in his own eyes" — foreshadow the moral collapse described in Judges?', 'It predicts that Israel would never properly centralize worship', 'It identifies individualistic moral autonomy as the root of covenant unfaithfulness, directly echoed in Judges 17:6 and 21:25', 'It simply allows for flexibility in worship during the wilderness period', 'It is Moses'' personal complaint about Israel''s behavior at Sinai', 'a', 'Judges 17:6 and 21:25 both record: "every man did that which was right in his own eyes" — the exact phrase Moses warned against in Deuteronomy 12:8. Moses identifies this attitude as the pre-conquest norm to be eliminated, and Judges documents its catastrophic persistence.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 6, 'What does the repeated emphasis on rejoicing before the LORD (Deuteronomy 12:7, 12, 18) reveal about the character of Old Testament worship?', 'It shows that worship was primarily a joyful communal celebration, not merely obligation or fear', 'Rejoicing was only required at the three pilgrimage feasts', 'Joy was an optional element dependent on individual temperament', 'Rejoicing before God was a Levitical duty, not a command for the whole congregation', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:12 — "And ye shall rejoice before the LORD your God." Repeated three times in the chapter, this command frames all covenant worship as fundamentally celebratory — a theme carried into the New Testament in Philippians 4:4 and the Psalms of Ascent.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 7, 'What does Deuteronomy 12:19 — "Take heed to thyself that thou forsake not the Levite as long as thou livest upon the earth" — reveal about Israel''s social covenant responsibilities?', 'The Levite''s welfare was inseparable from proper worship — neglecting him was equivalent to neglecting the ministry of God', 'The Levites were wealthy enough to care for themselves', 'This command only applied when the central sanctuary was in operation', 'The tribe of Levi was responsible for their own financial support through tithes only', 'a', 'The Levite had no tribal inheritance (Deuteronomy 12:12 — "the Levite that is within your gates; forasmuch as he hath no part nor inheritance with you"). Israel''s care for the Levite was a covenant obligation directly tied to maintaining faithful worship and the ministry of the word.'),
('Deuteronomy', 12, 'adults', 8, 'How does the phrase "whatsoever I command you, observe to do it: thou shalt not add thereto, nor diminish from it" (Deuteronomy 12:32) function as a canonical boundary marker?', 'It prohibits Israel from updating Moses'' laws in later generations', 'It establishes the sufficiency and finality of God''s revealed commands, warning against both addition and subtraction — echoed in Revelation 22:18-19', 'It was addressed only to the priests who handled the written Torah', 'It only applies to the specific laws about the central sanctuary in chapter 12', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 12:32 — "What thing soever I command you, observe to do it: thou shalt not add thereto, nor diminish from it." This formula of canonical closure appears also in Deuteronomy 4:2 and finds its New Testament parallel in Revelation 22:18-19, establishing Scripture''s own claim to sufficiency.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'kids', 1, 'What should Israel do if a prophet tells them to follow other gods, even if his sign or wonder comes true?', 'Not listen to him because God was testing them', 'Follow the prophet if the sign came true', 'Ask the priest to judge the prophet', 'Wait and see if a second sign happened', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:3 — "Thou shalt not hearken unto the words of that prophet...for the LORD your God proveth you, to know whether ye love the LORD your God with all your heart."'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What was to happen to a prophet who spoke lies in the name of other gods to lead Israel astray?', 'He was to be put to death', 'He was to be banished from Israel', 'He was to be made a slave', 'He was to pay a large fine', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:5 — "And that prophet, or that dreamer of dreams, shall be put to death; because he hath spoken to turn you away from the LORD your God."'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What should an Israelite do if even a close family member secretly invited them to worship other gods?', 'Not listen and report them', 'Listen but not obey', 'Pray for guidance first', 'Move to another city to avoid them', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:8-9 — "Thou shalt not consent unto him, nor hearken unto him...But thou shalt surely kill him; thine hand shall be first upon him to put him to death."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'teens', 1, 'According to Deuteronomy 13, what purpose does God allow false prophets with signs and wonders to serve?', 'To test whether Israel loves God with all their heart and soul', 'To judge Israel''s enemies by deceiving them', 'To demonstrate that only Levites could distinguish true from false prophecy', 'To prepare Israel for the arrival of the Messiah', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:3 — "for the LORD your God proveth you, to know whether ye love the LORD your God with all your heart and with all your soul."'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'teens', 2, 'What criterion does Deuteronomy 13 establish as the ultimate test of a true prophet — content or accuracy?', 'Content — a prophet who leads to other gods is false even if his signs come true', 'Accuracy — a prophet whose predictions come true is from God regardless of doctrine', 'Both equally — signs and sound doctrine must both be present', 'Neither — only the priest could authenticate a prophet', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:1-3 — Even if "the sign or the wonder come to pass, whereof he spake," the prophet is false if he says "Let us go after other gods." Doctrinal content, not miraculous power, is the ultimate test.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'teens', 3, 'What three categories of people who might incite idolatry does Deuteronomy 13 address?', 'A false prophet, a close family member, and wicked men of a city', 'A foreign king, a deceiving merchant, and a corrupt priest', 'An Amalekite spy, a Canaanite woman, and a hired sorcerer', 'A dreamer, a seer, and a soothsayer', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13 addresses: a prophet or dreamer (vv. 1-5), a family member or close friend (vv. 6-11), and sons of Belial who corrupt a whole city (vv. 12-18) — three concentric circles of threat from the religious leader, to the intimate, to the community.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'teens', 4, 'What was to happen to a city in Israel where all the inhabitants had been led into idolatry?', 'It was to be completely destroyed — people, animals, and all its spoil burned — becoming a heap forever', 'The guilty leaders were killed and the rest allowed to repent', 'The city was handed over to the Levites for purification', 'The inhabitants were exiled outside the borders of Israel', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:15-16 — "Thou shalt surely smite the inhabitants of that city with the edge of the sword, destroying it utterly...And thou shalt gather all the spoil of it into the midst of the street thereof, and shalt burn with fire the city."'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'teens', 5, 'Why was no spoil from a condemned idolatrous city to be taken by Israelites, according to Deuteronomy 13:17?', 'So that God''s fierce anger would turn away and He would show mercy and multiply Israel', 'So the Levites could later receive it as their portion', 'To prevent the idols from contaminating Israelite homes', 'Because all the spoil belonged to the conquering foreign nations', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:17 — "And there shall cleave nought of the cursed thing to thine hand: that the LORD may turn from the fierceness of his anger, and shew thee mercy, and have compassion upon thee."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 1, 'How does Deuteronomy 13:1-3 address the relationship between miraculous signs and doctrinal authority in a way that Paul echoes in Galatians 1:8?', 'Signs validate doctrine; Paul agrees with Moses that miracles confirm a message', 'Moses and Paul both insist doctrinal faithfulness supersedes miraculous credentials — even an angel preaching another gospel is accursed', 'Paul overturns Moses by saying the New Covenant abolishes the test of doctrine', 'Only Deuteronomy applies this principle; Paul uses different criteria', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:3 — even a wonder-working prophet who says "go after other gods" is to be rejected. Galatians 1:8 — "But though we, or an angel from heaven, preach any other gospel...let him be accursed." Both texts establish: doctrine over signs, content over credentials.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 2, 'What does the phrase "sons of Belial" (Deuteronomy 13:13) signify, and how does this term recur in the New Testament?', 'It means worthless or wicked men who reject God''s authority — 2 Corinthians 6:15 uses it as a name for Satan', 'It refers to a specific Canaanite tribe living in Israel', 'It describes Levites who had abandoned the priesthood', 'It is a legal term for men who had forfeited their tribal inheritance', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:13 — "Certain men, the children of Belial, are gone out from among you." 2 Corinthians 6:15 — "And what concord hath Christ with Belial?" Paul uses "Belial" as the embodiment of satanic opposition to God, drawing on this Deuteronomic idiom for radical godlessness.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 3, 'What does the command to execute even a beloved family member for soliciting idolatry (Deuteronomy 13:6-9) reveal about the exclusive claim of covenant loyalty?', 'Family loyalty must yield to covenant loyalty — God''s claim is absolute and supersedes all human relationships', 'Moses was legislating excessive harshness that Christ later abolished', 'The command was hyperbolic and never literally applied in Israel', 'It only applied to the Levitical tribe serving at the altar', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:6-8 — "If thy brother...or thy son, or thy daughter, or the wife of thy bosom...entice thee secretly, saying, Let us go and serve other gods...Thou shalt not consent unto him." Jesus cites a similar principle in Matthew 10:37 — "He that loveth father or mother more than me is not worthy of me" — covenant loyalty to God as the supreme loyalty.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 4, 'What is the legal principle established by "thine hand shall be first upon him" (Deuteronomy 13:9) in the context of an idolatrous family member?', 'The accuser bears primary responsibility for initiating judgment, preventing false accusation through personal cost', 'The eldest son always strikes first in capital cases', 'The high priest had to authorize the first blow in all executions', 'It was a symbolic gesture indicating the family''s innocence', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:9 — "thine hand shall be first upon him to put him to death, and afterwards the hand of all the people." The informant''s hand strikes first — this required personal conviction and carried personal cost, functioning as a safeguard against false accusation while removing the excuse of passing responsibility to others.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 5, 'How does the "herem" (ban/devoted thing) applied to the apostate city in Deuteronomy 13:16-17 connect to the fall of Jericho in Joshua 6?', 'The herem of Jericho was the paradigmatic application of this law — total destruction with nothing kept for personal use', 'Jericho''s herem was unrelated to Deuteronomy 13 since Jericho was a Canaanite city', 'Joshua modified the herem to allow silver and gold for the tabernacle treasury', 'The herem was suspended for Jericho because Rahab lived there', 'a', 'Joshua 6:17 — "the city shall be accursed, even it, and all that are therein, to the LORD." Achan''s sin in Joshua 7 is explicitly the violation of this herem principle — taking accursed things. Deuteronomy 13:17 directly informs the Jericho herem: no spoil, total destruction, the city never rebuilt.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 6, 'What does Moses mean by "to know whether ye love the LORD your God with all your heart" (Deuteronomy 13:3) regarding the nature of divine testing?', 'God discovers facts He did not previously know through testing', 'Testing reveals and demonstrates the true condition of the heart — both to the tested person and as covenant evidence', 'The test was a divine experiment to determine Israel''s future', 'It means God doubted Israel''s sincerity and needed external proof', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:3 — "the LORD your God proveth you, to know whether ye love the LORD." As with Abraham''s test (Genesis 22:12 — "now I know that thou fearest God"), divine testing does not supply God with new information but reveals and demonstrates covenant faithfulness, both for the individual and as public covenant record.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 7, 'How does Deuteronomy 13 function within the broader framework of Deuteronomy''s concern for covenant exclusivity (the First Commandment)?', 'It provides three case studies illustrating how the First Commandment''s demand for exclusive loyalty plays out across different social contexts', 'It is a standalone law code unrelated to the Decalogue', 'It addresses only political threats to Israel''s territorial integrity', 'It supplements the Second Commandment about graven images', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13 systematically applies Deuteronomy 5:7 — "Thou shalt have none other gods before me" — to three real-world scenarios: the religious professional (prophet), the intimate relationship (family), and the civic community (city). Each case intensifies the exclusivity of covenant loyalty.'),
('Deuteronomy', 13, 'adults', 8, 'What does Deuteronomy 13:18 — "when thou shalt hearken to the voice of the LORD thy God, to keep all his commandments...to do that which is right in the eyes of the LORD" — establish about the connection between obedience and divine compassion?', 'Obedience earns God''s mercy through merit', 'Covenant obedience is the condition through which God''s promised compassion and blessing flow — not merit but covenant faithfulness', 'The verse promises that Israel would always receive compassion regardless of behavior', 'It limits God''s compassion to the tribe of Judah alone', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:18 closes the chapter by linking obedience to divine mercy — "that the LORD may...shew thee mercy, and have compassion upon thee." This is not meritorious earning but covenant responsiveness: God''s grace flows through the channel of faithful obedience, consistent with the entire Deuteronomic covenant structure.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 14 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'kids', 1, 'Which animals could Israel eat according to Deuteronomy 14?', 'Animals that have a divided hoof and chew the cud', 'Any animal they could catch in the wild', 'Only animals offered at the tabernacle', 'Animals without horns or hooves', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:6 — "And every beast that parteth the hoof, and cleaveth the cleft into two claws, and cheweth the cud among the beasts, that ye shall eat."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'kids', 2, 'What were Israelites to do with a tenth of all they produced from the land each year?', 'Bring it to the place God chose and eat it before Him with their family', 'Give it all to the priests', 'Store it for the winter in their own houses', 'Sell it in the marketplace', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:22-23 — "Thou shalt truly tithe all the increase of thy seed...And thou shalt eat before the LORD thy God...the tithe of thy corn, of thy wine, and of thine oil."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'kids', 3, 'Every third year, where was the tithe to be stored and for whom?', 'In the gates of each city, for the Levite, the stranger, the fatherless, and the widow', 'In the temple treasury in Jerusalem', 'At the home of the eldest tribal leader', 'In pits dug near the tabernacle', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:28-29 — "At the end of three years thou shalt bring forth all the tithe of thine increase the same year, and shalt lay it up within thy gates: And the Levite...and the stranger, and the fatherless, and the widow...shall come, and shall eat and be satisfied."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'teens', 1, 'Why did God forbid Israel from cutting themselves or shaving between their eyes for the dead?', 'Because they were a holy people, a special treasure to God, not to mourn like the pagans', 'Because it was harmful to the body and God cared for their health', 'Because such practices were reserved for the priests alone', 'Because mourning was forbidden in the law of Moses', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:1-2 — "Ye are the children of the LORD your God: ye shall not cut yourselves, nor make any baldness between your eyes for the dead. For thou art an holy people unto the LORD thy God."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'teens', 2, 'Why could the camel, rabbit, and rock badger not be eaten even though they chew the cud?', 'Because they do not have a divided hoof', 'Because they were considered vermin', 'Because they were too small to be worth slaughtering', 'Because they were unclean based on their habitat', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:7 — "the camel, and the hare, and the coney: for they chew the cud, but divide not the hoof; therefore they are unclean unto you."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'teens', 3, 'What rule governed eating fish — what features made them clean?', 'Fins and scales — fish with fins and scales could be eaten; all others were unclean', 'Only freshwater fish from Israelite rivers were permitted', 'Fish could be eaten without restriction unlike land animals', 'Only fish caught in nets rather than by hook were clean', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:9-10 — "These ye shall eat of all that are in the waters: all that have fins and scales shall ye eat: And whatsoever hath not fins and scales ye may not eat; it is unclean unto you."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'teens', 4, 'What provision was made for an Israelite whose journey to the central sanctuary was too long to carry his tithes in kind?', 'He could exchange his tithe for silver and use the silver to buy whatever he desired at the sanctuary', 'He was excused from the tithe entirely that year', 'He could send his tithe by messenger with the Levites', 'He could keep his tithe until the next year''s feast', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:24-26 — "And if the way be too long for thee...then shalt thou turn it into money...and shalt bestow that money for whatsoever thy soul lusteth after, for oxen, or for sheep, or for wine, or for strong drink, or for whatsoever thy soul desireth."'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'teens', 5, 'What assurance does Deuteronomy 14:29 give about the third-year tithe given to the poor and the Levite?', 'That the LORD thy God will bless thee in all the work of thy hand', 'That Israel will receive double the following year', 'That God will multiply the flocks of those who give', 'That the Levites will pray for the givers at the sanctuary', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:29 — "And the Levite...and the stranger, and the fatherless, and the widow...shall come, and shall eat and be satisfied; that the LORD thy God may bless thee in all the work of thine hand which thou doest."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 1, 'How do the clean and unclean food laws of Deuteronomy 14 relate to Israel''s holiness calling stated in verse 2?', 'The dietary code was a daily embodied reminder of Israel''s separation from the nations as God''s holy possession', 'The laws were purely hygienic with no theological significance', 'They were temporary regulations for the wilderness period only', 'They applied only to the priestly class who served at the altar', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:2 — "thou art an holy people unto the LORD thy God, and the LORD hath chosen thee to be a peculiar people unto himself." The dietary laws enacted separation in the most basic daily act — eating — making holiness tangible and habitual in covenant life.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 2, 'How does the New Testament handle the clean and unclean food distinctions of Deuteronomy 14, and what theological principle governs the transition?', 'The laws are permanently binding on all Christians exactly as stated', 'Acts 10 and Mark 7:19 indicate the ceremonial food laws are fulfilled in Christ, with holiness now expressed through internal purity rather than external food restriction', 'Paul simply declared all food laws irrelevant without theological reasoning', 'The laws were transferred to the church as fasting regulations', 'a', 'Mark 7:19 — "(This he said, making all meats clean.)" Acts 10:15 — "What God hath cleansed, that call not thou common." The food laws pointed to Israel''s separation and Christ''s body is now the holy community set apart — the purpose is fulfilled, not abolished arbitrarily.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological and social function of the annual tithe feast described in Deuteronomy 14:22-27?', 'It was a joyful covenant meal celebrating God''s provision, reinforcing communal identity and worship at the central sanctuary', 'It was a tax collected by the priests for temple maintenance', 'It served as an economic system to equalize wealth between tribes', 'It was a penalty paid for land use within God''s territory', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:23 — "thou shalt eat before the LORD thy God...that thou mayest learn to fear the LORD thy God always." The feast before God combined worship, family joy, Levite inclusion, and covenant education — making gratitude, generosity, and reverence integral to Israel''s economic life.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of the third-year tithe being stored "within thy gates" (Deuteronomy 14:28) rather than taken to the central sanctuary?', 'It created a local welfare system ensuring the most vulnerable — Levites, strangers, orphans, widows — were cared for in every community', 'It was a compromise for those too lazy to travel to the sanctuary', 'It indicated the third-year tithe was less holy than the annual tithe', 'It was stored locally only until the priests could collect it', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:28-29 describes a triennial tithe deposited locally for Levites, resident aliens, fatherless, and widows. This created a decentralized social safety net functioning alongside the central sanctuary system, ensuring covenant care reached every community regardless of distance.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 5, 'How does the prohibition "thou shalt not seethe a kid in his mother''s milk" (Deuteronomy 14:21) illustrate the broader principle of honoring natural boundaries in creation?', 'It prohibits a specific Canaanite ritual practice and upholds the natural bond between mother and offspring as worthy of respect', 'It is purely a health regulation against cross-contamination of dairy and meat', 'It was only a priestly ceremonial law with no application to ordinary Israelites', 'It was symbolic of Israel''s separation from Edom who practiced this', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:21 — "Thou shalt not seethe a kid in his mother''s milk." This command, appearing three times in the Torah (also Exod. 23:19; 34:26), forbids using the very source of the animal''s nurture as the medium of its death — a principle of natural reverence that also guarded against a known Canaanite cultic practice.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 6, 'What does the permission to sell unclean carcasses to foreigners (Deuteronomy 14:21) reveal about the nature of Israel''s food laws?', 'The laws were covenantal and ethnic — binding on Israel as God''s covenant people, not universal moral laws imposed on all humanity', 'All people regardless of nation were under the same food restrictions', 'The food laws were merely hygienic and foreigners were exempt because they had different health needs', 'Israel could sell unclean food to foreigners as economic exploitation of non-Israelites', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:21 — "thou shalt not eat of any thing that dieth of itself: thou shalt give it unto the stranger that is in thy gates, that he may eat it; or thou mayest sell it unto an alien." The distinction confirms the laws are covenantal identity markers for Israel, not universal natural law.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 7, 'How does the Deuteronomic tithe system differ from and complement the Levitical tithe system outlined in Numbers 18?', 'Numbers 18 describes a tithe given directly to Levites; Deuteronomy 14 describes a tithe consumed by the worshipper and family at the sanctuary — the two likely represent different tithes or aspects of the same system', 'They are identical and describe the same tithe from two perspectives', 'Deuteronomy replaces the Numbers tithe entirely with a new system', 'Numbers 18 applies only to priests while Deuteronomy 14 applies only to Levites', 'a', 'Numbers 18:21-24 gives a tenth to Levites. Deuteronomy 14:22-27 describes a tithe eaten at the sanctuary by the worshipper. Many scholars identify these as two distinct tithes (some see a third in Deuteronomy 14:28-29), together representing Israel''s comprehensive system of worship-linked generosity.'),
('Deuteronomy', 14, 'adults', 8, 'What does the phrase "thou mayest not eat within thy gates the tithe of thy corn" (Deuteronomy 14:23) reveal about the relationship between physical eating and spiritual formation?', 'Eating the tithe at the sanctuary before God was itself an act of worship — the physical act of communal feasting formed covenant consciousness and reverence', 'The command was purely logistical to prevent spoilage during transport', 'Eating at the sanctuary was required to prevent Levites from being cheated', 'The sanctuary meal was only for the priests who needed sustenance for their duties', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 14:23 — "thou shalt eat...before the LORD thy God...that thou mayest learn to fear the LORD thy God always." The command makes the act of eating a pedagogy of the fear of God. Physical covenant meals form spiritual identity — a pattern carried forward into the Lord''s Supper in 1 Corinthians 11:26.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 15 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'kids', 1, 'How often did God command that debts be cancelled in Israel?', 'Every seven years', 'Every fifty years', 'Every ten years', 'Every year at Passover', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:1 — "At the end of every seven years thou shalt make a release."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'kids', 2, 'What did God say Israel should do when they saw a poor person among them?', 'Open wide their hand and lend freely to help them', 'Report them to the city elders for assistance', 'Give them work in the fields', 'Send them to the Levites for support', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:11 — "For the poor shall never cease out of the land: therefore I command thee, saying, Thou shalt open thine hand wide unto thy brother, to thy poor, and to thy needy, in thy land."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'kids', 3, 'After how many years of service was a Hebrew servant to be set free?', 'In the seventh year', 'In the tenth year', 'After twenty years', 'After five years', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:12 — "And if thy brother, an Hebrew man, or an Hebrew woman, be sold unto thee, and serve thee six years; then in the seventh year thou shalt let him go free from thee."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'teens', 1, 'What was the "release" commanded every seventh year, and who was exempt from it?', 'All loans to fellow Israelites were to be forgiven; foreigners were not covered by this release', 'All servants were to be freed; foreigners could remain servants', 'All tithes were suspended; only the temple tax continued', 'All fields were to lie fallow; the priestly portions were exempted', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:2-3 — "every creditor that lendeth ought unto his neighbour shall release it...Of a foreigner thou mayest exact it again: but that which is thine with thy brother thine hand shall release."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'teens', 2, 'What attitude did God say would be wicked in an Israelite''s heart as the seventh year approached?', 'Thinking evil against a poor neighbor and refusing to lend because the year of release was near', 'Hoarding food in fear of the debt cancellation year', 'Selling all property before the seventh year to avoid losses', 'Trying to collect debts before the year was announced', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:9 — "Beware that there be not a thought in thy wicked heart, saying, The seventh year, the year of release, is at hand; and thine eye be evil against thy poor brother, and thou givest him nought."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'teens', 3, 'What was the promise attached to faithful lending to the poor regardless of the approaching sabbatical year?', 'God would bless the lender in all his works and in all he put his hand to', 'The borrower''s debt would be transferred to the sanctuary', 'God would restore double what was lent', 'The lender would be given an extra year before the debt was released', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:10 — "Thou shalt surely give him, and thine heart shall not be grieved when thou givest unto him: because that for this thing the LORD thy God shall bless thee in all thy works, and in all that thou puttest thine hand unto."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'teens', 4, 'What were masters commanded to give a freed Hebrew servant when releasing him in the seventh year?', 'To furnish him liberally from the flock, threshing floor, and winepress', 'Only the wages owed for his service', 'A certificate of freedom and one month''s food', 'Whatever the servant requested up to a set limit', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:13-14 — "And when thou sendest him out free from thee, thou shalt not let him go away empty: Thou shalt furnish him liberally out of thy flock, and out of thy floor, and out of thy winepress."'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'teens', 5, 'What was the ritual by which a Hebrew servant could voluntarily choose to remain with his master permanently?', 'His master would bore his ear through with an awl at the door, and he would serve him forever', 'He would sign a written contract before the city elders', 'He would offer a sacrifice at the tabernacle in his master''s name', 'He would shave his head as a sign of renewed servitude', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:17 — "Then thou shalt take an awl, and thrust it through his ear unto the door, and he shall be thy servant for ever. And also unto thy maidservant thou shalt do likewise."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 1, 'What is the covenantal basis for the sabbatical debt release, and how does it reflect the structure of Israel''s land theology?', 'The seven-year cycle mirrors the Sabbath principle — the land and economic life both rest under God''s ownership, freeing debts reflects that all wealth ultimately belongs to God', 'It was an economic policy designed to prevent the accumulation of interest', 'The release reflected the amnesty granted by the king at his coronation', 'It was based on the seven-year famine cycle of Genesis', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:1-2 — "At the end of every seven years thou shalt make a release." As the seventh-day Sabbath and the seventh-year fallow both express that time and land belong to God (Lev. 25:23), the debt release extends this principle to economic life — all belongs to God, and His people mirror His generosity.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of the condition "if thou shalt hearken diligently unto the voice of the LORD" (Deuteronomy 15:5) in relation to the promise that there would be no poor among them?', 'The absence of poverty was a covenant blessing contingent on faithful obedience — not an unconditional social promise', 'God promised that diligence alone, not obedience to the law, would eliminate poverty', 'The verse guarantees economic equality as a result of the sabbatical year alone', 'The condition was aspirational and not expected to be fully met', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:4-5 — "Save when there shall be no poor among thee...Only if thou carefully hearken unto the voice of the LORD thy God." The elimination of poverty was the covenant ideal — not a flat unconditional guarantee — dependent on the whole community practicing God''s commands about generosity and release.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 3, 'How does Jesus use Deuteronomy 15:11 — "the poor shall never cease out of the land" — in John 12:8, and what does this reveal about the relationship between the Mosaic and messianic eras?', 'Jesus quotes Moses to rebuke Judas, showing that the Mosaic social ethic remains valid while also pointing to a unique moment — his own burial — that transcends normal ethical calculations', 'Jesus cites it to abolish the sabbatical year debt release as no longer necessary', 'The verse is used to justify abandoning care for the poor in the messianic age', 'Jesus uses it to reaffirm that the Levitical tithe system was still binding on his disciples', 'a', 'John 12:8 — "For the poor always ye have with you; but me ye have not always." Jesus quotes Deuteronomy 15:11 not to discourage care for the poor but to establish that Mary''s anointing was a unique eschatological act. Moses'' ongoing realism about poverty is affirmed, not overturned.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 4, 'What does the ear-piercing ceremony in Deuteronomy 15:17 signify typologically in relation to Christ''s servanthood?', 'The voluntary slave who chooses bondage out of love for his master typifies Christ, who voluntarily took the form of a servant (Philippians 2:7) for love of those He serves', 'It was a purely civic ceremony with no messianic significance', 'The pierced ear signified the slave''s acceptance of Mosaic law as permanently binding', 'It was a penalty imposed on servants who had mismanaged their master''s property', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:16-17 — "if he say unto thee, I will not go away from thee; because he loveth thee...then thou shalt take an awl, and thrust it through his ear." Psalm 40:6 — "mine ears hast thou opened" — and Philippians 2:7 — "took upon him the form of a servant" — both draw on this imagery of voluntary, love-motivated servitude fulfilled in Christ.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 5, 'What does the repeated phrase "thine hand" in Deuteronomy 15:2, 3, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 — "thou shalt open thine hand wide" — reveal about the practical nature of biblical generosity?', 'Generosity is not merely an attitude but a concrete bodily act — the opened hand is the outward sign of a generous heart', 'The phrase is a legal formula indicating signed financial agreements', 'It refers only to the formal release ceremony at the year''s end', 'The repeated phrase is a stylistic device with no deeper significance', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:11 — "Thou shalt open thine hand wide unto thy brother, to thy poor, and to thy needy." The physical metaphor of the open hand versus the closed fist recurs throughout the chapter to embody covenantal generosity as a visible, tangible action, not just an inner disposition.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 6, 'How does the command to release servants in Deuteronomy 15:12-14 build on the Exodus narrative and what theological argument does Moses use to motivate obedience?', 'Moses grounds the law in Israel''s own experience of slavery in Egypt — "thou wast a bondman in the land of Egypt" — making memory of redemption the motivation for liberating others', 'The release law is based on economic necessity to prevent labor shortages', 'Moses grounds it in the creation of Adam as a free being who must never be permanently enslaved', 'The motivation given is purely practical — freed servants would become productive tax-paying citizens', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:15 — "And thou shalt remember that thou wast a bondman in the land of Egypt, and the LORD thy God redeemed thee: therefore I command thee this thing to day." The Exodus becomes the moral foundation for Israel''s treatment of the enslaved — those who were liberated must liberate others.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 7, 'What is the spiritual danger Moses identifies in Deuteronomy 15:9 — "thine eye be evil against thy poor brother" — and how does Jesus develop this imagery in Matthew 6:22-23?', 'The "evil eye" represents covetousness and stinginess — Jesus uses the same idiom to warn that a miserly heart darkens the whole soul', 'It refers to the sin of envy when the poor prosper', 'Jesus uses the phrase to describe occult spiritual attack against believers', 'Moses uses it in a purely legal sense without spiritual significance', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:9 — "thine eye be evil against thy poor brother." Matthew 6:22-23 — "The light of the body is the eye...if thine eye be evil, thy whole body shall be full of darkness." Both texts use the eye as a moral lens: the generous eye illumines; the miserly eye darkens. Jesus develops the Deuteronomic idiom into a teaching on single-minded generosity.'),
('Deuteronomy', 15, 'adults', 8, 'What does the firstling legislation at the end of Deuteronomy 15:19-23 reveal about the comprehensive scope of covenant consecration in daily Israelite life?', 'Even the reproduction of livestock fell under covenant law — the firstborn of every flock and herd belonged to God, making every new life a reminder of divine ownership', 'The firstling law was a separate legal code unrelated to the sabbatical year provisions', 'Only the firstling of cattle was consecrated; sheep and goats were exempt', 'The firstling law applied only in years when the tithe had not been paid', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 15:19 — "All the firstling males that come of thy herd and of thy flock thou shalt sanctify unto the LORD thy God." The consecration of firstlings extended God''s ownership claim to the very reproductive cycle of Israel''s economy, making every birth a covenant act of recognition that life itself comes from and belongs to God.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 16 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'kids', 1, 'What feast did God command Israel to observe in the month of Abib to remember leaving Egypt?', 'The Passover', 'The Feast of Weeks', 'The Feast of Tabernacles', 'The Day of Atonement', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:1 — "Observe the month of Abib, and keep the passover unto the LORD thy God: for in the month of Abib the LORD thy God brought thee forth out of Egypt by night."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'kids', 2, 'What feast did Israel celebrate seven weeks after the harvest began?', 'The Feast of Weeks', 'The Feast of Unleavened Bread', 'The Feast of Tabernacles', 'The Feast of Firstfruits', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:9-10 — "Seven weeks shalt thou number unto thee...And thou shalt keep the feast of weeks unto the LORD thy God with a tribute of a freewill offering of thine hand."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'kids', 3, 'What did Moses command when appointing judges in Deuteronomy 16?', 'That they judge the people with just and righteous judgment', 'That they only hear cases involving money', 'That they serve for only one year at a time', 'That they be chosen only from the tribe of Levi', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:18-19 — "Judges and officers shalt thou make thee...and they shall judge the people with just judgment. Thou shalt not wrest judgment."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'teens', 1, 'How many days was the Feast of Unleavened Bread to last, and why was it called by that name?', 'Seven days — because no leavened bread was eaten during those days, only unleavened bread', 'Three days — as a symbol of the three-day journey from Egypt', 'Fourteen days — corresponding to both Passover and its aftermath', 'Eight days — added to account for the Sabbath within the feast', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:3 — "Thou shalt eat no leavened bread with it; seven days shalt thou eat unleavened bread therewith...that thou mayest remember the day when thou camest forth out of the land of Egypt all the days of thy life."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'teens', 2, 'What three groups were specifically commanded to rejoice at the Feast of Weeks?', 'The Israelite worshipper with his household, the Levite, and the stranger, the fatherless, and the widow', 'Only the adult male Israelites', 'The priests and their families exclusively', 'The men of each tribe and their firstborn sons', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:11 — "And thou shalt rejoice before the LORD thy God, thou, and thy son, and thy daughter, and thy manservant, and thy maidservant, and the Levite that is within thy gates, and the stranger, and the fatherless, and the widow."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'teens', 3, 'How long was the Feast of Tabernacles to last, and after what agricultural events was it celebrated?', 'Seven days, after gathering in the threshing floor and winepress — the end of all harvests', 'Three days, at the beginning of the planting season', 'Fourteen days, after the grain harvest alone', 'Five days, at the spring equinox', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:13 — "Thou shalt observe the feast of tabernacles seven days, after that thou hast gathered in thy corn and thy wine."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'teens', 4, 'What rule about giving applied to each of the three annual feasts?', 'Every man was to give as he was able, according to the blessing of the LORD', 'A fixed amount was required regardless of income', 'Only those who owned land were required to bring offerings', 'One lamb per household regardless of wealth', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:17 — "Every man shall give as he is able, according to the blessing of the LORD thy God which he hath given thee."'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'teens', 5, 'What specific abuses in the administration of justice does Deuteronomy 16:19 prohibit?', 'Wresting judgment, respecting persons, and taking a gift (bribe) which blinds the wise', 'Judging cases in secret and without witnesses', 'Allowing foreigners to serve as judges in Israelite courts', 'Permitting the accused to choose their own judge', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:19 — "Thou shalt not wrest judgment; thou shalt not respect persons, neither take a gift: for a gift doth blind the eyes of the wise, and pervert the words of the righteous."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 1, 'How do the three pilgrimage feasts of Deuteronomy 16 — Passover, Weeks, and Tabernacles — structure Israel''s annual calendar theologically?', 'They mark the three great redemptive acts — liberation from Egypt, the giving of the law, and the wilderness provision — making Israel''s year a liturgical re-enactment of salvation history', 'They were primarily agricultural festivals that God later attached religious meaning to', 'They corresponded to the three phases of the conquest of Canaan', 'They were adapted from Canaanite harvest festivals already observed in the land', 'a', 'The three feasts (Passover = redemption from Egypt; Weeks/Pentecost = associated with Sinai/first fruits; Tabernacles = wilderness sojourn) structured Israel''s time around the narrative of God''s saving acts, as Paul sees fulfilled in Christ: "Christ our passover is sacrificed for us" (1 Corinthians 5:7).'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 2, 'What is the New Testament fulfillment of the Feast of Weeks (Pentecost) that Acts 2 records, and how does it connect to Deuteronomy 16?', 'The outpouring of the Holy Spirit at Pentecost fulfills the feast as the giving of the new covenant law written on the heart, just as Sinai gave the written law', 'Pentecost in Acts 2 is unrelated to the Mosaic feast and coincidental in timing', 'The feast was fulfilled by Christ''s resurrection which happened at Pentecost', 'Acts 2 replaces the Feast of Weeks with a new Christian observance with no connection to Deuteronomy', 'a', 'Acts 2:1-4 — "And when the day of Pentecost was fully come...they were all filled with the Holy Ghost." Just as Sinai gave the law fifty days after Passover, the Spirit was given fifty days after Christ''s Passover sacrifice — the new covenant law written on the heart (Jeremiah 31:33; 2 Corinthians 3:3).'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 3, 'What does the command in Deuteronomy 16:16 — "Three times in a year shall all thy males appear before the LORD thy God in the place which he shall choose" — reveal about the relationship between worship and community?', 'Mandatory communal assembly for worship before God maintained covenant unity and prevented the privatization of religion', 'The command excluded women from meaningful worship participation', 'It was primarily a census-taking mechanism disguised as worship', 'The command applied only to landowners who had produce to bring', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:16 — "they shall not appear before the LORD empty." The three annual assemblies of all Israel at the central sanctuary created national covenant community — regularly gathering the whole people before God prevented individualism, tribalism, and syncretism. Women and households participated (verses 11, 14), though males bore the representative duty.'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 4, 'What does the Feast of Tabernacles instruction to "rejoice in thy feast" (Deuteronomy 16:14) paired with the reminder of former bondage in Egypt (verse 12) suggest about the nature of Christian joy?', 'Genuine joy is always rooted in the memory of redemption — knowing where one came from deepens gratitude for where one stands', 'Joy was only commanded when circumstances were materially prosperous', 'The feast''s joy was conditional on military victories during the year', 'Rejoicing was a priestly duty, not a command for the whole congregation', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:12, 14 — "thou shalt remember that thou wast a bondman in Egypt...thou shalt rejoice in thy feast." The pattern of joy grounded in remembered redemption anticipates Philippians 4:4 — "Rejoice in the Lord alway" — where Paul''s own imprisonment cannot quench joy rooted in Christ''s redemptive act.'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 5, 'How does Deuteronomy 16:18-20 — "justice, and only justice, thou shalt follow" (ESV) — function within the broader social ethics of the Torah?', 'It establishes an absolute commitment to impartial justice as a cornerstone of covenant community life, directly opposing the corruption that defined Canaanite and Egyptian society', 'It applies only to judges and has no implication for ordinary Israelites', 'It was primarily a warning against foreign legal systems being imported into Israel', 'Justice was defined differently for Israelites and resident aliens', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:20 — "That which is altogether just shalt thou follow, that thou mayest live, and inherit the land." The connection between justice and land tenure is explicit — covenant possession of the land required covenant justice in the land. Amos 5:24 — "let judgment run down as waters" — develops this as the prophetic standard for national faithfulness.'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 6, 'What is the significance of prohibiting Asherah poles and sacred pillars "beside the altar of the LORD" (Deuteronomy 16:21-22)?', 'Mixing Canaanite fertility symbols with the worship of the LORD was the specific syncretism Moses warned against — even adjacent placement defiled true worship', 'Asherah poles were merely aesthetically offensive, not spiritually dangerous', 'The prohibition only applied in the wilderness before entering Canaan', 'Sacred pillars were forbidden only if they depicted human figures', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:21-22 — "Thou shalt not plant thee a grove of any trees near unto the altar of the LORD thy God...Neither shalt thou set thee up any image; which the LORD thy God hateth." The prohibition targets proximity — the danger was not only outright idolatry but the blending of Canaanite fertility religion with Yahwistic worship, which is exactly what Israel later did in Judges and Kings.'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 7, 'How does the repetition of "the place which the LORD shall choose" throughout Deuteronomy 16 function as a critique of unauthorized worship sites?', 'It anchors all legitimate worship to God''s self-determined location, systematically delegitimizing the high places that would later corrupt Israel', 'It was a temporary restriction until Israel built the tabernacle at Shiloh', 'The phrase allowed any place where the ark was temporarily stationed', 'It delegated the choice to the high priest rather than to God directly', 'a', 'The phrase "the place which the LORD thy God shall choose" appears in Deuteronomy 16:2, 6, 7, 11, 15, 16 — six times in one chapter. This insistence on God''s chosen place systematically excludes the high places of Canaan and anticipates the prophetic critique of those who offered on every high hill (1 Kings 14:23; Hosea 4:13).'),
('Deuteronomy', 16, 'adults', 8, 'What does the inclusion of the Levite, stranger, fatherless, and widow in the feast celebrations (Deuteronomy 16:11, 14) reveal about the social theology of Old Testament worship?', 'Covenant worship was inherently inclusive of the economically and socially marginalized — joy before God was not a privilege of the landed class alone', 'The inclusion was a concession that later became standard only in the postexilic period', 'The marginalized groups were allowed to observe but not participate actively in the feasts', 'Their inclusion was conditional on their work contribution to the harvest', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 16:11 — "the Levite...and the stranger, and the fatherless, and the widow, that are among you." The same four vulnerable groups repeatedly named in Deuteronomy''s social legislation (10:18; 14:29; 24:19-21; 26:12-13) are explicitly included in the joy of the three feasts, making covenant worship inseparable from covenant justice.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 17 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'kids', 1, 'What kind of animal was forbidden to be sacrificed to God?', 'A blemished or defective animal', 'A firstborn animal', 'An animal bought from a foreigner', 'A white animal', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:1 — "Thou shalt not sacrifice unto the LORD thy God any bullock, or sheep, wherein is blemish, or any evilfavouredness: for that is an abomination unto the LORD thy God."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'kids', 2, 'How many witnesses were required before someone could be put to death for worshipping idols?', 'Two or three witnesses', 'Five witnesses', 'Only one trusted witness', 'The testimony of a priest alone', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:6 — "At the mouth of two witnesses, or three witnesses, shall he that is worthy of death be put to death; but at the mouth of one witness he shall not be put to death."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'kids', 3, 'What was the king of Israel commanded NOT to multiply?', 'Horses, wives, and gold and silver', 'Servants and cattle', 'Weapons and chariots only', 'Grain and wine', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:16-17 — "But he shall not multiply horses to himself...Neither shall he multiply wives to himself...Neither shall he greatly multiply to himself silver and gold."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'teens', 1, 'What were the hard cases brought to the central sanctuary to be decided by, and what was the penalty for refusing their verdict?', 'The priests and the judge at the central sanctuary decided hard cases; refusing their verdict carried the death penalty', 'The tribal elders at the city gate decided all cases', 'Cases were decided by lot before the tabernacle', 'The king had final authority on all difficult legal matters', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:8-12 — "the priests the Levites, and unto the judge that shall be in those days...And the man that will do presumptuously, and will not hearken unto the priest...that man shall die."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'teens', 2, 'What specific sin involving heavenly bodies does Deuteronomy 17:3 condemn?', 'Worshipping the sun, moon, or stars — the host of heaven — which God had not commanded', 'Using the stars to predict weather or harvests', 'Teaching children the names of the constellations', 'Making calendars based on the movement of the moon', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:3 — "And hath gone and served other gods, and worshipped them, either the sun, or moon, or any of the host of heaven, which I have not commanded."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'teens', 3, 'Who cast the first stone in the execution of someone found guilty of idolatry, and what was the significance of this?', 'The hands of the witnesses were first upon him — the accusers bore primary responsibility for the execution', 'The high priest cast the first stone as a representative of God', 'The king authorized and initiated the execution', 'The city elders cast the first stone as a sign of civic authority', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:7 — "The hands of the witnesses shall be first upon him to put him to death, and afterward the hands of all the people." This prevented frivolous accusation — the witness bore personal liability for the life they took.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'teens', 4, 'What was the future king of Israel required to do with a copy of God''s law?', 'Write a copy of the law himself and read it all the days of his life', 'Memorize the entire Torah by his coronation day', 'Engrave the law on a pillar at the palace entrance', 'Send a copy to every tribal chief annually', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:18-19 — "And it shall be, when he sitteth upon the throne of his kingdom, that he shall write him a copy of this law in a book...And he shall read therein all the days of his life."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'teens', 5, 'What three prohibitions on the king in Deuteronomy 17 were specifically violated by Solomon, leading to his downfall?', 'Multiplying horses (1 Kings 10:26), multiplying wives (1 Kings 11:3), and multiplying silver and gold (1 Kings 10:14)', 'Levying taxes, drafting soldiers, and making foreign alliances', 'Building cities, accumulating land, and expanding the priesthood', 'Rewriting the law, building high places, and appointing foreign judges', 'a', '1 Kings 10:26 — Solomon had 1,400 chariots and 12,000 horses. 1 Kings 11:3 — 700 wives and 300 concubines. 1 Kings 10:14 — 666 talents of gold annually. Every prohibition of Deuteronomy 17:16-17 was violated by Solomon, and 1 Kings 11:4 records the result: "his wives turned away his heart."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 1, 'How does the law of the king in Deuteronomy 17:14-20 function as a prophetic critique of the monarchy before Israel even had a king?', 'It establishes a constitutional monarchy under the Torah — the king is a covenant servant under the law, not an absolute sovereign above it', 'It reluctantly allows a king while expressing no opinion about the institution itself', 'It predicts the failure of the monarchy and commands Israel to remain a theocracy', 'It was added to Deuteronomy after Saul''s coronation as a retrospective critique', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:18-20 — the king must write and read the law "that his heart be not lifted up above his brethren, and that he turn not aside from the commandment." This defines Israelite kingship as servant leadership under God''s law — the king as the greatest covenant keeper, not the greatest law-giver. 1 Samuel 8 and the failure of the monarchy is the outworking of ignoring this standard.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 2, 'What does the prohibition of multiplying horses (Deuteronomy 17:16) and the reference to not returning to Egypt for them reveal about the theology of national security in Deuteronomy?', 'Military power secured through human means (Egyptian horses) contradicts covenant trust in God as Israel''s defender — security must rest on obedience, not armaments', 'The prohibition was economic — horses were too expensive for Israel''s budget', 'Only Egyptian horses were forbidden; horses from other nations were permitted', 'The law only applied during the wilderness period when horses were impractical', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:16 — "he shall not multiply horses to himself, nor cause the people to return to Egypt to the purpose of multiplying horses." Isaiah 31:1 — "Woe to them that go down to Egypt for help; and stay on horses." The horse symbolized self-reliant military power in the ANE; Deuteronomy grounds national security in covenant faithfulness, not military hardware.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 3, 'How does the two-or-three-witness rule of Deuteronomy 17:6 shape New Testament legal and ecclesial practice?', 'Jesus cites it in Matthew 18:16 for church discipline; Paul cites it in 2 Corinthians 13:1 and 1 Timothy 5:19 — the principle governs both civic and ecclesial justice', 'The rule was abolished in the New Testament as a relic of Mosaic civil law', 'The New Testament replaces it with a single reliable witness standard', 'Paul uses it only in financial disputes, not doctrinal or moral cases', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:6 — "At the mouth of two witnesses, or three witnesses, shall he...be put to death." Matthew 18:16 — "take with thee one or two more, that in the mouth of two or three witnesses every word may be established." 2 Corinthians 13:1 — "In the mouth of two or three witnesses shall every word be established." The Mosaic evidentiary standard becomes the framework for Christian community accountability.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 4, 'What is the theological significance of the king writing "a copy of this law in a book out of that which is before the priests the Levites" (Deuteronomy 17:18)?', 'The king''s copy comes from the priestly canonical text — the king''s authority is subordinate to and derived from God''s word, not equal to it', 'The king''s copy was a summary document he composed himself', 'Writing the copy was a purely ceremonial act without ongoing significance', 'It indicates the king had interpretive authority over the law equal to the priests', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:18-19 — the king copies from the priestly text and reads it daily "that he may learn to fear the LORD his God." The king''s authority flows from submission to God''s word — he is the ideal disciple before he is the national leader. This anticipates Joshua 1:8 — "This book of the law shall not depart out of thy mouth."'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 5, 'How does Deuteronomy 17:9 — appeal to "the priests the Levites, and unto the judge that shall be in those days" — establish a precedent for constitutional appeals courts in Israel?', 'It creates a tiered judicial system with a supreme court at the central sanctuary for cases too difficult for local courts, ensuring unified legal interpretation', 'It abolishes local courts and centralizes all justice at the sanctuary', 'It gives the king final judicial authority above the priests', 'It applies only to cases involving the priesthood itself', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:8-9 — "If there arise a matter too hard for thee in judgment...thou shalt come unto the priests...and unto the judge." This establishes what Jehoshaphat later formalizes in 2 Chronicles 19:8-10 — a supreme judicial body at Jerusalem handling appeals, giving Israel a constitutional structure for maintaining covenant justice.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 6, 'What does the phrase "that his heart be not lifted up above his brethren" (Deuteronomy 17:20) reveal about the Deuteronomic vision of leadership?', 'Covenant leadership is fundamentally fraternal — the king is a brother among brothers, not a sovereign above subjects, and humility before God''s law prevents tyranny', 'The phrase only prohibits the king from wearing royal insignia', 'It means the king should not be taller in stature than his officials', 'It restricts the king from having more land than other tribal leaders', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:20 — "That his heart be not lifted up above his brethren, and that he turn not aside from the commandment." The fraternal model of kingship anticipates Jesus'' teaching in Mark 10:42-44 — "whosoever will be great among you, shall be your minister" — the greatest as servant, rooted in this Deuteronomic vision.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 7, 'How does Deuteronomy 17:12 — the death penalty for refusing the verdict of the central court — establish the principle of the rule of law over individual conscience in covenant community?', 'It establishes that communal legal order requires submission to authoritative interpretation — individual defiance of constituted authority is a capital threat to covenant community', 'It shows Moses believed individual moral judgment was always inferior to priestly authority', 'It was a temporary measure that ended when Israel had a king', 'It only applied to cases involving the death penalty, not civil disputes', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 17:12 — "the man that will do presumptuously, and will not hearken unto the priest...even that man shall die: and thou shalt put away the evil from Israel." This is not blind submission to authority but recognition that covenant community requires authoritative interpretation of God''s law; presumptuously defying that order destroys the community''s legal foundation.'),
('Deuteronomy', 17, 'adults', 8, 'How does Saul''s reign specifically violate the spirit of Deuteronomy 17''s law of the king in ways that David''s does not?', 'Saul acts presumptuously above God''s word (1 Samuel 13:13; 15:23) — the exact sin Deuteronomy 17:12 condemns; David, though morally flawed, consistently submits to God''s word as the ultimate authority', 'Saul multiplied horses and wives more than David did', 'David had more copies of the law than Saul, making him more obedient', 'Saul failed because he did not have priests write his copy of the law', 'a', '1 Samuel 13:13 — "thou hast not kept the commandment of the LORD thy God." 1 Samuel 15:23 — "rebellion is as the sin of witchcraft, and stubbornness is as iniquity and idolatry." Deuteronomy 17:20 says the king''s heart must not be lifted up — Saul''s defining failure is exactly this presumption. David''s heart, despite his sins, is consistently described as toward God (1 Kings 11:4).');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 18 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'kids', 1, 'Why did the Levites not receive a land inheritance in Israel?', 'The LORD was their inheritance', 'They were given gold instead of land', 'They lived in the tabernacle permanently', 'They were given cities but no farmland', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:2 — "Therefore shall they have no inheritance among their brethren: the LORD is their inheritance, as he hath said unto them."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'kids', 2, 'What did God say He would raise up for Israel in place of the sorcerers and diviners of the nations?', 'A prophet from among their brothers', 'An angel to speak to them directly', 'A new set of stone tablets', 'A council of wise elders', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:15 — "The LORD thy God will raise up unto thee a Prophet from the midst of thee, of thy brethren, like unto me; unto him ye shall hearken."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'kids', 3, 'What practices did God forbid Israel to imitate from the nations around them?', 'Divination, witchcraft, enchantments, and consulting the dead', 'Wearing foreign clothing', 'Speaking foreign languages', 'Trading with foreign merchants', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:10-11 — "There shall not be found among you any one that maketh his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, or that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch...or a necromancer."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'teens', 1, 'What portions of sacrifices were the priests entitled to receive from the people''s offerings?', 'The shoulder, the two cheeks, and the maw of every animal sacrificed', 'The firstborn of every animal', 'The right leg and the breast of peace offerings', 'The fat of every sacrifice', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:3 — "And this shall be the priest''s due from the people...whether it be ox or sheep; and they shall give unto the priest the shoulder, and the two cheeks, and the maw."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'teens', 2, 'What right did a Levite have if he moved from his town to the central sanctuary to minister there?', 'He could minister alongside the other Levites and receive equal portions', 'He had to wait three years before being allowed to serve', 'He could only serve if the existing Levites approved him', 'He lost his country portions when he moved to the sanctuary', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:6-8 — "And if a Levite come from any of thy gates...and come with all the desire of his mind unto the place which the LORD shall choose; Then he shall minister in the name of the LORD his God...they shall have like portions to eat."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'teens', 3, 'What test does Moses give in Deuteronomy 18 to determine whether a prophet''s words were from God?', 'If what the prophet spoke did not come to pass, he was a false prophet who had spoken presumptuously', 'If the prophet could perform a sign or wonder, his message was from God', 'If the priest verified the prophet''s message against the written law', 'If the tribal elders unanimously approved the prophet''s words', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:22 — "When a prophet speaketh in the name of the LORD, if the thing follow not, nor come to pass, that is the thing which the LORD hath not spoken, but the prophet hath spoken it presumptuously: thou shalt not be afraid of him."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'teens', 4, 'What ten forbidden occult practices are listed in Deuteronomy 18:10-11?', 'Passing children through fire, divination, observing times, enchanting, witchcraft, charming, consulting familiar spirits, wizardry, and necromancy', 'Astrology, dream interpretation, reading omens, blood sacrifice to demons, idol worship, and prayer to the dead', 'Magic, fortune-telling, cursing, blessing in a pagan god''s name, sacrificing animals at night, mixing potions', 'Sorcery, reading tea leaves, summoning storms, selling amulets, worshipping at high places', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:10-11 — "that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch, Or a charmer, or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer" — plus making children pass through fire — nine categories condemned as abominations.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'teens', 5, 'What was the consequence for a prophet who spoke in God''s name words that God had not commanded him to say?', 'That prophet shall die', 'He was to be flogged and exiled', 'He was stripped of prophetic office and given to the priests for judgment', 'He paid a fine equal to the cost of the false prophecy''s effects', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:20 — "But the prophet, which shall presume to speak a word in my name, which I have not commanded him to speak...even that prophet shall die."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 1, 'How does Acts 3:22-23 apply the promise of "a prophet like unto Moses" (Deuteronomy 18:15) to Jesus Christ?', 'Peter quotes Deuteronomy 18:15 directly and applies it to the resurrection of Jesus, declaring that whoever does not hear this Prophet shall be destroyed from among the people', 'Acts 3 sees Deuteronomy 18:15 as fulfilled by John the Baptist', 'The verse is applied to the apostles collectively as Moses'' successors', 'Peter uses the verse to justify the authority of the Jerusalem church council', 'a', 'Acts 3:22-23 — "For Moses truly said unto the fathers, A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up unto you of your brethren, like unto me; him shall ye hear in all things whatsoever he shall say unto you." Peter declares this fulfilled in Jesus, and the warning of verse 23 — destruction for those who refuse — carries eschatological weight in the apostolic proclamation.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 2, 'In what specific ways does Jesus fulfill the "prophet like Moses" typology of Deuteronomy 18:15-18?', 'Both are mediators of a covenant, both receive revelation from God directly, both speak the words God commands, both intercede for the people — and Jesus surpasses Moses as Hebrews 3:3 states', 'Jesus only fulfills the prophecy in his role as teacher, not as mediator', 'The fulfillment is purely in Jesus'' healing miracles paralleling Moses'' signs in Egypt', 'Jesus fulfills it only at the transfiguration when Moses appears with him', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:18 — "I will raise them up a Prophet...and will put my words in his mouth; and he shall speak unto them all that I shall command him." John 12:49 — "For I have not spoken of myself; but the Father which sent me, he gave me a commandment, what I should say." Hebrews 3:5-6 — "Moses verily was faithful...as a servant...But Christ as a son over his own house."'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological significance of the statement that the Levite''s "portion" before the LORD and his "heritage" are the LORD himself (Deuteronomy 18:2)?', 'It establishes a model of ministry in which the minister''s ultimate security rests in God''s sufficiency rather than material inheritance — the pattern Paul follows in Philippians 4:11-12', 'It indicates Levites were spiritually superior to other Israelites', 'It means Levites were excused from all material concerns and lived by miraculous provision', 'The phrase is metaphorical and merely means Levites received tithes instead of land', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:2 — "the LORD is their inheritance." Philippians 4:11 — "I have learned, in whatsoever state I am, therewith to be content." Paul''s contentment in all circumstances reflects the Levitical principle that God''s servants whose inheritance is God himself are free from the anxiety that attaches to material security.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 4, 'How does Deuteronomy 18:9-14 frame the prohibition of occult practices — as primarily moral, ritual, or epistemological?', 'Primarily epistemological — the nations sought knowledge of the divine will through these means; Israel was to receive that knowledge through God''s prophet, not pagan intermediaries', 'Purely ritual — the practices defiled the land ceremonially', 'Solely moral — the practices were inherently evil acts comparable to murder', 'Primarily political — the practices gave foreign priests power over Israel''s military decisions', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:14 — "For these nations, which thou shalt possess, hearkened unto observers of times, and unto diviners: but as for thee, the LORD thy God hath not suffered thee so to do." The contrast is epistemological: pagan nations used divination to access divine knowledge; Israel received God''s word through the covenant prophet. Occult practice was thus an act of unfaithfulness to God''s communication channel.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 5, 'What does the phrase "I will put my words in his mouth" (Deuteronomy 18:18) establish about the nature of biblical prophecy?', 'True prophecy is verbal and propositional — God places specific words in the prophet''s mouth, establishing verbal inspiration as the model for all canonical prophecy', 'The phrase is metaphorical and only means the prophet received general impressions from God', 'It applies only to Deuteronomy 18''s specific prophet like Moses, not to prophecy generally', 'It indicates the prophet composed his messages freely and God later endorsed them', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:18 — "I will put my words in his mouth; and he shall speak unto them all that I shall command him." This defines canonical prophecy as verbal — God''s words placed in the prophet''s mouth. Jeremiah 1:9 — "I have put my words in thy mouth" — confirms this is the standard model of prophetic inspiration.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 6, 'How does the dual test of Deuteronomy 13 (doctrinal faithfulness) and Deuteronomy 18 (predictive accuracy) together form a complete framework for evaluating prophetic claims?', 'Chapter 13 guards against doctrinally deceptive prophets who perform signs; chapter 18 guards against those who make false predictions — together they require both doctrinal orthodoxy and predictive fulfillment', 'The two tests are redundant — predictive accuracy is sufficient to validate any prophet', 'Chapter 13 supersedes chapter 18; doctrine is the only test needed', 'The tests apply to different categories: ch. 13 to oral prophets, ch. 18 to written prophets', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 13:3 tests doctrine: even a sign-working prophet who promotes other gods is false. Deuteronomy 18:22 tests fulfillment: a prophet whose words do not come to pass is false. The two together form a comprehensive criterion — a true prophet must preach the true God AND speak words that come to pass.'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 7, 'What is the rhetorical and theological function of God''s statement "I will hear him" (Deuteronomy 18:17) about Israel''s request for an intermediary prophet?', 'God validates Israel''s instinct that direct divine encounter is overwhelming — the prophet as mediator is God''s gracious accommodation to human finitude, not a concession to faithlessness', 'God''s statement indicates Israel sinned by asking for a prophet rather than direct revelation', 'It means God would only speak through the prophet and was withdrawing from any direct relationship with Israel', 'It was a concession to Israel''s weakness that was later revoked in the New Covenant', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 18:16-17 — Israel said at Horeb "let me not hear again the voice of the LORD my God, neither let me see this great fire any more, that I die not. And the LORD said unto me, They have well spoken that which they have spoken." God affirms the request — the prophet system is God''s gift to bridge the gap between divine holiness and human fragility, fulfilled ultimately in the Word made flesh (John 1:14).'),
('Deuteronomy', 18, 'adults', 8, 'How does the Levitical provision system in Deuteronomy 18:1-8 relate to Paul''s argument in 1 Corinthians 9:13-14 about the right of ministers to material support?', 'Paul explicitly appeals to this principle — "they which minister about holy things live of the things of the temple" — to establish the right of gospel ministers to financial support from the congregation', 'Paul argues the Levitical system was abolished and ministers have no right to support', 'The connection is indirect; Paul bases his argument only on the command of Jesus', 'Paul uses it to argue that ministers should receive sacrificed animals, not money', 'a', '1 Corinthians 9:13-14 — "Do ye not know that they which minister about holy things live of the things of the temple...Even so hath the Lord ordained that they which preach the gospel should live of the gospel." Paul draws a direct line from Deuteronomy 18''s Levitical provisions to the New Testament principle of congregational support for ministry — the pattern of the old covenant informs the new.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 19 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'kids', 1, 'Why did God command Israel to set up cities of refuge?', 'So that a person who killed someone by accident could flee there and be safe', 'So that the poor could live there without paying taxes', 'So that criminals could be imprisoned safely', 'So that foreigners would have a place to live in Israel', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:4 — "And this is the case of the slayer, which shall flee thither, that he may live: Whoso killeth his neighbour ignorantly, whom he hated not in time past."'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'kids', 2, 'How many cities of refuge was Israel first to set aside in Canaan?', 'Three cities', 'Six cities', 'Twelve cities', 'One city', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:2 — "Thou shalt separate three cities for thee in the midst of thy land, which the LORD thy God giveth thee to possess it."'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'kids', 3, 'What was to happen to someone who moved his neighbor''s boundary marker?', 'He was cursed', 'He was fined double', 'He was banished from the city', 'He was made to restore the boundary stone only', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:14 — "Thou shalt not remove thy neighbour''s landmark, which they of old time have set in thine inheritance, which thou shalt inherit in the land that the LORD thy God giveth thee to possess it." (The curse is made explicit in Deuteronomy 27:17.)'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'teens', 1, 'What example does Moses give of an accidental killing that would allow someone to flee to a city of refuge?', 'A man whose axe head flew off while chopping wood and struck his neighbor who died', 'A man who accidentally shot an arrow that killed a passerby', 'A man whose horse bolted and trampled another person', 'A man who accidentally knocked someone off a roof', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:5 — "As when a man goeth into the wood with his neighbour to hew wood, and his hand fetcheth a stroke with the axe to cut down the tree, and the head slippeth from the helve, and lighteth upon his neighbour, that he die; he shall flee unto one of those cities, and live."'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'teens', 2, 'Under what conditions could the avenger of blood pursue and kill the man who fled to a city of refuge?', 'If the elders of his city judged that he had killed with hatred and deliberate intent', 'If the dead man''s family had at least two witnesses against him', 'If the man left the city of refuge before the year of release', 'If the high priest ruled that the death was not accidental', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:11-12 — "But if any man hate his neighbour, and lie in wait for him...Then the elders of his city shall send and fetch him thence, and deliver him into the hand of the avenger of blood, that he may die."'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'teens', 3, 'How many more cities of refuge was God willing to add if Israel''s territory expanded?', 'Three more cities, for a total of six', 'Six more cities, for a total of nine', 'One more city in each new territory', 'As many as the king requested', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:9 — "Then shalt thou add three cities more for thee, beside these three." This anticipated the possibility of Israel expanding to fulfill the full extent of the promised territory.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'teens', 4, 'What principle of false witness did Moses establish — what happens to a false witness?', 'The false witness receives the punishment he intended to bring upon the innocent person', 'The false witness pays a fine and is publicly shamed', 'The false witness is exiled to one of the cities of refuge', 'The false witness is imprisoned until the innocent person decides his fate', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:19 — "Then shall ye do unto him, as he had thought to have done unto his brother: so shalt thou put the evil away from among you."'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'teens', 5, 'What famous principle of proportional justice is stated at the end of Deuteronomy 19?', 'Life for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot', 'Mercy triumphs over judgment in all civil cases', 'Greater punishment for greater crimes, lesser for lesser', 'Restitution double the value of what was taken', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:21 — "And thine eye shall not pity; but life shall go for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological purpose of the cities of refuge, and how do they typologically point to Christ?', 'They protect the innocent from vigilante justice — typologically Christ is the refuge to whom sinners flee from the penalty of the law, and in Him the avenger has no claim', 'They were primarily administrative centers for processing legal cases efficiently', 'They served as military strongholds garrisoned by the Levites', 'Their typological significance was limited to Israel''s civic life with no messianic application', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:4-6 — "lest the avenger of the blood pursue the slayer, while his heart is hot, and overtake him...and slay him." Hebrews 6:18 — "who have fled for refuge to lay hold upon the hope set before us." The city of refuge prefigures Christ as the place of safety for those who flee to him — in him the avenger''s claim is satisfied and the fugitive is secure.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 2, 'What does the requirement to keep the roads to the cities of refuge in good repair (implied in Deuteronomy 19:3 — "thou shalt prepare thee a way") reveal about the nature of covenant justice?', 'Accessible justice requires infrastructure — the community bore responsibility to ensure the innocent could actually reach protection, not merely that protection theoretically existed', 'Road maintenance was a military requirement unrelated to the cities of refuge', 'The requirement showed that the Levites who maintained the roads had judicial authority', 'Road preparation was only symbolic and never literally required', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:3 — "Thou shalt prepare thee a way, and divide the coasts of thy land...into three parts, that every slayer may flee thither." Jewish tradition (Makkot 10b) records that roads to cities of refuge were kept clear, wide, and well-signposted. Justice that cannot be reached provides no protection — the covenant community was responsible for making refuge accessible.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 3, 'How does Deuteronomy 19:14 — the prohibition on moving boundary stones — relate to the broader covenant theology of land as divine gift?', 'Moving a boundary stone is not merely theft but a desecration of God''s territorial arrangement — the land divisions were covenantally ordered and to move them was to act against God''s assignment', 'It was a purely civic property law with no theological dimension', 'The prohibition only applied to boundaries established by Moses, not later surveyors', 'It was a practical regulation to prevent agricultural disputes', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:14 — "which they of old time have set in thine inheritance, which thou shalt inherit in the land that the LORD thy God giveth thee." The phrase "the LORD thy God giveth thee" frames the boundary as divinely given — moving it is transgression against God''s own territorial order. Proverbs 22:28 — "Remove not the ancient landmark, which thy fathers have set" — extends the principle beyond Israel.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 4, 'How does the lex talionis (eye for eye) in Deuteronomy 19:21 function as a principle of justice rather than a license for personal revenge?', 'It establishes proportionality and limits retaliation — the punishment must fit the crime exactly, no more — and it was administered by judges, not private individuals', 'It authorizes individuals to take personal vengeance proportional to the harm received', 'It was a maximum punishment that judges could reduce but never exceed', 'It applies only to false witness cases, not to bodily harm generally', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:21 — "life shall go for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth." The context (false witness before judges, verse 17) makes clear this is judicial, not personal. The lex talionis limits retaliation: the punishment must be proportionate. Jesus does not abolish it but addresses personal relationships: "I say unto you, That ye resist not evil" (Matthew 5:38-39) — moving from the courtroom to the heart.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 5, 'What does the distinction between premeditated murder and accidental homicide in Deuteronomy 19 reveal about the moral framework of the Torah?', 'Intent matters morally — the Torah distinguishes deliberate malice from tragic accident, reflecting a moral psychology that sees the heart''s purpose as legally and spiritually determinative', 'The Torah treats all killing equally regardless of intent', 'Only the outcome (death) matters in the Torah''s legal framework', 'The distinction was a later rabbinic development not present in Moses'' original law', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:4-6, 11-12 — the accidental killer "hated not" his neighbor; the murderer "hate his neighbour, and lie in wait." The same act (homicide) receives different legal treatment based on the actor''s heart. This moral psychology underlies the entire Deuteronomic ethic and is developed by Jesus in the Sermon on the Mount (Matthew 5:21-22).'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 6, 'How does the principle in Deuteronomy 19:19 — the false witness receives the punishment he intended for the innocent — reflect a theology of divine poetic justice?', 'God''s justice operates on the principle that the pit dug for others is dug for the digger — malicious intent returns on the malicious actor, as seen throughout Scripture (Esther 7:10; Psalm 7:15-16)', 'It is purely a deterrence mechanism with no theological significance', 'The principle was designed to protect the rich from false accusations by the poor', 'It only applied to capital cases, not to lesser punishments', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:19 — "Then shall ye do unto him, as he had thought to have done unto his brother." Psalm 7:15-16 — "He made a pit, and digged it, and is fallen into the ditch which he made." Esther 7:10 — Haman hanged on the gallows he built for Mordecai. The pattern of self-consuming evil is a consistent theological motif from Deuteronomy through the wisdom literature.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 7, 'What is the rhetorical function of "so shalt thou put the evil away from among you" repeated in Deuteronomy 19:19, and how does this phrase appear throughout Deuteronomy?', 'It is a covenant formula signaling that the law''s purpose is communal purity — evil must be actively removed from the covenant community to preserve its holiness', 'It is a figure of speech meaning the guilty person''s reputation would be destroyed', 'The formula indicates the person was removed from the community physically by exile', 'It refers specifically to the removal of idols and altars', 'a', 'The formula "put the evil away from among you" appears in Deuteronomy 13:5; 17:7, 12; 19:19; 21:21; 22:21-24; 24:7 — a refrain structuring the law codes. It frames capital punishment not as revenge but as covenant purification — the community''s corporate holiness requires the active removal of that which corrupts it. Paul applies the same principle in 1 Corinthians 5:13.'),
('Deuteronomy', 19, 'adults', 8, 'What does Deuteronomy 19:15 — "one witness shall not rise up against a man for any iniquity" — establish about the epistemological standards required for covenant justice?', 'It establishes that legal certainty in matters of life and liberty requires corroborated testimony — the covenant community must not act on uncorroborated accusation', 'It means that a single eyewitness is legally insufficient even if completely truthful', 'It was designed to protect the wealthy who could afford multiple witnesses', 'It applied only to capital cases and not to property disputes', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 19:15 — "at the mouth of two witnesses, or at the mouth of three witnesses, shall the matter be established." This epistemological standard protects the innocent from the power of a single accusation and is foundational for biblical justice. Jesus applies it in John 8:17; Paul in 2 Corinthians 13:1; and the principle governs church discipline in Matthew 18:16.');

-- ═══ Deuteronomy Chapter 20 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'kids', 1, 'What did God tell Israel NOT to do when they saw a large enemy army with horses and chariots?', 'Not be afraid, because God was with them', 'Turn and run to the cities of refuge', 'Send messengers to ask for peace first', 'Choose the bravest soldiers to fight', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:1 — "When thou goest out to battle against thine enemies, and seest horses, and chariots, and a people more than thou, be not afraid of them: for the LORD thy God is with thee, which brought thee up out of the land of Egypt."'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'kids', 2, 'Who was allowed to go home and not fight in a battle if he had just built a new house or planted a vineyard?', 'The man who had not yet dedicated his house or enjoyed his vineyard', 'Only the firstborn son of each family', 'Any man who had never fought before', 'The city elders who were too old to fight', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:5-6 — "What man is there that hath built a new house, and hath not dedicated it? let him go and return to his house...And what man is he that hath planted a vineyard, and hath not yet eaten of it? let him also go and return unto his house."'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'kids', 3, 'When Israel offered peace to a distant city, what happened if the city accepted?', 'The people became servants and worked for Israel', 'The city was destroyed anyway', 'The people were allowed to keep their land', 'The city paid a tribute of gold and silver', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:11 — "And it shall be, if it make thee answer of peace, and open unto thee, then it shall be, that all the people that is found therein shall be tributaries unto thee, and they shall serve thee."'),
-- Teens
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'teens', 1, 'What did the priest say to the army before battle to encourage them?', 'Hear, O Israel, ye approach this day unto battle against your enemies: let not your hearts faint, fear not, for the LORD goeth with you', 'Fight with courage and no enemy shall stand before you', 'Remember the covenant of Abraham and you shall not be defeated', 'The LORD will send an angel before you to destroy your enemies', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:3-4 — "And shall say unto them, Hear, O Israel, ye approach this day unto battle against your enemies: let not your hearts faint, fear not, and do not tremble...For the LORD your God is he that goeth with you, to fight for you against your enemies, to save you."'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'teens', 2, 'What four categories of men were exempted from military service and sent home before battle?', 'One who built a new house; one who planted a vineyard; one who betrothed a wife; and one who was fearful and fainthearted', 'The firstborn, the elderly, the sick, and recent converts', 'Levites, judges, city elders, and craftsmen building the sanctuary', 'Men with young children, farmers with pending harvests, merchants in debt, and the lame', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:5-8 — new house (not dedicated), new vineyard (not yet eaten), new betrothal (not yet married), and "what man is there that is fearful and fainthearted? let him go and return unto his house."'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'teens', 3, 'What was the difference in treatment between distant cities and Canaanite cities when conquered?', 'Distant cities: offer peace first, enslave if accepted, kill all males if rejected but spare women and children; Canaanite cities: utterly destroy everything — no survivors', 'Both types of cities received the same treatment regardless of location', 'Distant cities were to be destroyed but Canaanite cities could be spared if they converted', 'Only Canaanite cities needed to be offered peace before attack', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:10-15 (distant cities — offer peace, take tribute or kill males) vs. 20:16-17 (Canaanite cities — "thou shalt save alive nothing that breatheth...thou shalt utterly destroy them").'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'teens', 4, 'Why did God command the total destruction of the Canaanite nations specifically?', 'So that they would not teach Israel to commit their abominations to their gods, causing Israel to sin', 'Because they were guilty of crimes against other nations', 'To fulfill the covenant with Abraham who had asked for the land to be cleared', 'Because the Canaanites had rejected God''s offer of peace three times', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:18 — "That they teach you not to do after all their abominations, which they have done unto their gods; so should ye sin against the LORD your God."'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'teens', 5, 'What kind of trees were Israel specifically forbidden to cut down during a siege, and why?', 'Fruit trees — because a man eats of them and they are not at war with Israel', 'Olive trees — because they were used for the sanctuary lamp', 'Cedar trees — because they were sacred to God', 'Palm trees — because they were used for the Feast of Tabernacles', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:19 — "thou shalt not destroy the trees thereof by forcing an axe against them: for thou mayest eat of them, and thou shalt not cut them down (for the tree of the field is man''s life)."'),
-- Adults
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological significance of the priest''s speech in Deuteronomy 20:3-4, and how does the presence of a religious official before battle differ from the military customs of surrounding nations?', 'The priest''s address grounds Israel''s courage in God''s faithfulness rather than military prowess — unlike pagan auguries seeking favorable omens, the priest proclaims God''s active presence as the basis for courage', 'The priest''s role was purely ceremonial and had no practical effect on troop morale', 'The speech was given to satisfy a legal requirement before warfare could begin', 'The presence of a priest was Israel''s equivalent of a military chaplain with no theological distinction from pagan practices', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:3-4 — "For the LORD your God is he that goeth with you, to fight for you against your enemies, to save you." The priest does not offer omens but proclaims covenant promise — God who brought Israel out of Egypt fights for them. This contrasts with Canaanite pre-battle divination and grounds military courage in theological conviction rather than auspicious signs.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 2, 'What does the exemption of the "fearful and fainthearted" (Deuteronomy 20:8) reveal about God''s strategy for holy warfare?', 'God fights with a purified, willing remnant rather than a large army of mixed motivation — quality of faith, not quantity of troops, determines victory', 'The exemption was a humanitarian concession to those with anxiety disorders', 'It showed that Israel''s military was entirely volunteer-based', 'The fearful were exempted to prevent them from committing war crimes', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:8 — "lest his brethren''s heart faint as well as his heart." This principle is demonstrated in Judges 7 when Gideon''s 32,000 were reduced to 300 — God wins with the few who trust Him rather than the many who fight in their own strength. The theology of holy warfare is that God''s power is magnified through human weakness (2 Corinthians 12:9).'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 3, 'How does the tiered peace offer for distant cities (Deuteronomy 20:10-15) reflect a more restrained approach to warfare than the total destruction applied to Canaanite cities?', 'It shows that Deuteronomy''s warfare ethics are not uniformly genocidal — a peace-first, negotiation principle governs dealings with non-Canaanite peoples, with total destruction reserved for a specific theological purpose', 'The peace offer was a propaganda tactic, not a genuine option', 'Both distant and Canaanite cities were to be offered peace before attack', 'The distinction was purely geographic, not theological', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:10 — "When thou comest nigh unto a city to fight against it, then proclaim peace unto it." The peace offer to distant nations establishes a principle that Israel was not to be aggressor nations. The herem applied to Canaan specifically because of the theological contamination risk (v. 18), not as a universal rule of warfare.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 4, 'What does the protection of fruit trees during siege warfare (Deuteronomy 20:19-20) reveal about the scope of biblical ethics?', 'Covenant ethics extend to the natural environment — unnecessary destruction of the food-bearing creation is forbidden, establishing a principle of environmental restraint within warfare', 'It was a purely practical regulation to preserve Israel''s future food supply', 'The law applied only to Israelite trees, not trees in enemy territory', 'It showed Moses'' agricultural knowledge about the long time needed to regrow orchards', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:19 — "for the tree of the field is man''s life." The rhetorical question — "Is the tree of the field a man, that thou shouldest besiege it?" — establishes the tree''s innocence. This principle of non-combatant status for the natural world anticipates later just war theory and reflects a covenantal stewardship ethic extending beyond human society.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 5, 'How does the command to utterly destroy the Canaanite nations (Deuteronomy 20:16-17) relate to the theology of divine judgment and how do Christian interpreters typically understand it?', 'The Canaanites had filled up the measure of their iniquity (Genesis 15:16) — the conquest was God''s judicial execution of a condemned people through Israel as His instrument of judgment, a unique historical act not a general warfare principle', 'It establishes genocide as a legitimate warfare option for righteous nations in all ages', 'The command was later revoked by the prophets as inconsistent with God''s character', 'It applied only to the original seven Canaanite nations and had no theological significance beyond that historical moment', 'a', 'Genesis 15:16 — "the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet full." By the conquest, the time of judgment had come. Deuteronomy 20:17-18 specifies both the scope (utterly destroy) and the reason (lest they teach abominations). Christian interpreters generally see this as a unique, historically bounded act of divine judgment — not a template for Christian warfare.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological connection between the new-house exemption (Deuteronomy 20:5), the new-vineyard exemption (v. 6), and the new-betrothal exemption (v. 7), and what covenant value do they express?', 'They protect the covenant blessings of home, land, and family from being permanently forfeited through early death in war — shalom (wholeness) in each domain must be experienced before it can be sacrificed', 'They were economic regulations to prevent excessive military conscription from damaging Israel''s agricultural output', 'They applied only to the first generation entering Canaan, not to subsequent wars', 'They expressed the principle that soldiers should be motivated by what they were defending', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:5-7 — the three exemptions protect the three spheres of covenant blessing: home (new house), livelihood (vineyard), and family (betrothed wife). The pattern anticipates the full shalom vision of Deuteronomy 28 and Micah 4:4 — "every man under his vine and under his fig tree." War must not permanently rupture the covenant blessings it is meant to protect.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 7, 'How does the priestly exhortation "let not your hearts faint" in Deuteronomy 20:3 relate to the repeated command "be strong and of a good courage" given to Joshua in Joshua 1?', 'Joshua 1 directly applies the Deuteronomic warfare theology — courage is grounded in God''s presence and promise, not human strength, and the priest''s pre-battle word becomes the standard for all covenant leadership', 'Joshua 1 replaces the priestly speech with a prophetic oracle and has no connection to Deuteronomy 20', 'The phrases are stylistically similar but theologically unrelated', 'The command to courage in Joshua 1 is addressed to soldiers while Deuteronomy 20 only addresses the priests', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:3 — "let not your hearts faint, fear not." Joshua 1:6, 7, 9 — "Be strong and of a good courage...only be thou strong and very courageous...Be strong and of a good courage; be not afraid, neither be thou dismayed: for the LORD thy God is with thee whithersoever thou goest." Both ground courage in the covenant formula "God is with thee," making Deuteronomy 20 the theological foundation for Joshua''s entire leadership.'),
('Deuteronomy', 20, 'adults', 8, 'What does the phrase "the LORD thy God hath delivered it into thine hands" (implied in Deuteronomy 20:13 — "the LORD thy God doth deliver it into thine hands") reveal about the agency structure of holy warfare?', 'God is the primary agent and Israel the secondary instrument — the battle is God''s and the victory is declared as given before it is experienced, requiring faith to act on a promised reality', 'It means Israel should wait passively for God to win the battle without fighting', 'The phrase indicates military victory was guaranteed regardless of Israel''s obedience or tactics', 'It was a liturgical formula with no bearing on the actual military engagement', 'a', 'Deuteronomy 20:13 — "And when the LORD thy God hath delivered it into thine hands." The perfect tense of God''s deliverance precedes the battle — the victory is declared as accomplished from God''s side before it unfolds on the human side. This is the structure of faith in holy warfare: acting on God''s declared reality, as seen in Joshua 6:2 — "I have given into thine hand Jericho" — before the walls fell.');

